  "776": {
    "p": "The Zeal of Dr. Tasa",
    "len": 5
  },
  "777": {
    "p": "[161]",
    "len": 1
  },
  "778": {
    "h2": "CHAPTER XXI THE ZEAL OF DR. TASA",
    "len": 7
  },
  "779": {
    "p": "I entered my tent. How awfully alone I was! I should never find him again in the bottom of the camera or in the midst of postage stamps! I should never hear his little voice, prompting me with “Miferino.” I should never carry him astride the battlement, or on the crown of my hat. The imperial tomb was empty except for the white cotton bed!",
    "len": 65
  },
  "780": {
    "p": "I couldn’t sleep. After I don’t know how long the moon rose. I got up to look at the clock. It was midnight. Fiam had been walking four hours. How far had he gone?",
    "len": 36
  },
  "781": {
    "p": "The firing continued every now and then. “Little thunder,” I thought, remembering the queer idea of my friend. Every few minutes I looked at the clock. One o’clock passed; two o’clock passed. I was getting anxious. I thought an hour had gone by—it was five minutes.",
    "len": 49
  },
  "782": {
    "p": "At half-past two I began to listen. A quarter to three, three, a quarter past three——",
    "len": 17
  },
  "783": {
    "p": "[162]",
    "len": 1
  },
  "784": {
    "p": "I thought he hadn’t found the mine, and I almost felt glad at the idea that I might see him again.",
    "len": 22
  },
  "785": {
    "p": "Half-past three. The minutes seemed like eternity. Twenty-five minutes to four. Twenty minutes to four——",
    "len": 17
  },
  "786": {
    "p": "It was (I shall never forget it) at precisely thirteen minutes to four when the night was lighted by an immense brilliant blue light. A few seconds later the whole earth shook and a horrible explosion rent the air. Then silence.",
    "len": 41
  },
  "787": {
    "p": "It wasn’t long before the trumpets blew. The camp was all commotion. Commands were issued, confused with shouts. These, I made out, were joyful.",
    "len": 25
  },
  "788": {
    "p": "“The mine has been fired! The mine has been fired!” they repeated again and again.",
    "len": 15
  },
  "789": {
    "p": "The ranks formed. The regiments drew up in line of march. The officers galloped about. The flags were unfurled.",
    "len": 19
  },
  "790": {
    "p": "At dawn the columns moved—fresh and eager, as if starting off for the first encounter.",
    "len": 16
  },
  "791": {
    "p": "The terrible pass was traversed by the soldiers singing while the bayonets glistened in the rising sun. Two hours later we were safely outside the [163] mountainous defile, and were joined by the main army.",
    "len": 35
  },
  "792": {
    "p": "The enemy was forced to give battle, and was defeated.",
    "len": 10
  },
  "793": {
    "p": "That evening they all feasted in the general’s tent. All the officers were happy. I alone was sad.",
    "len": 19
  },
  "794": {
    "p": "After a while they began to ask, Who could have blown up the mine? Some one said:",
    "len": 17
  },
  "795": {
    "p": "“The soldiers sent to explore returned without finding anything.”",
    "len": 9
  },
  "796": {
    "p": "“Perhaps,” another suggested, “it blew up of itself on account of poor construction.”",
    "len": 13
  },
  "797": {
    "p": "“No,” said a third. “It was blown up by the enemy; they thought we were on the march, near the mine.”",
    "len": 21
  },
  "798": {
    "p": "I arose and said solemnly:",
    "len": 5
  },
  "799": {
    "p": "“I know who blew up the mine and made your victory and escape possible.”",
    "len": 14
  },
  "800": {
    "p": "“Tell us, tell us!” they shouted in chorus. “Who?”",
    "len": 9
  },
  "801": {
    "p": "“It was Fiam, who....”",
    "len": 4
  },
  "802": {
    "p": "“Who is that?” asked twenty voices at once. “Who is our hero and our rescuer? How did you know him?”",
    "len": 20
  },
  "803": {
    "p": "“It is,” I proceeded firmly, “the Haji of an old willow tree that....” A tumult of laughter greeted [164] me. Even the general joined in. They thought I was joking. The general cried:",
    "len": 33
  },
  "804": {
    "p": "“Still more legends, ha, ha!”",
    "len": 5
  },
  "805": {
    "p": "“I am in earnest,” I said, turning to him, and couldn’t help adding, “It was the Haji of Funato, your Haji.”",
    "len": 22
  },
  "806": {
    "p": "The laughter increased. “Legends, superstitions, fancies,” I heard in the midst of the hilarity.",
    "len": 14
  },
  "807": {
    "p": "I was so bewildered I didn’t know whether to get angry or laugh with them.",
    "len": 16
  },
  "808": {
    "p": "Suddenly I felt a touch on my shoulder. I turned to see an officer looking attentively at me. “My name is Tasa. Let me feel your pulse. Show me your tongue. I recommend a little ice on the head.”",
    "len": 39
  },
